{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01AxSGqM4aVWNUQVfxFpBPDS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01N1E3gFuJXNNDVksQaxYH7q","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/6-8a6c985/feedback.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":15948,"cache_read_input_tokens":66121,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":15948,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Mec9R64nuL6YcE5gmCxs41","session_id":"dda4a6e7-7d44-4b1e-8d84-edc63f9f063b","uuid":"31d301d9-c78e-43cd-8c2f-a2271b446f5b"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QspZ3mJVK2GHKH8uLDDQ4a","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Improvement Plan — Iteration 7\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Two failures remain at 66.7% accuracy. One is a genuine algorithm gap (suffix fragment survival in dedup), the other is primarily an evaluation harness bug (filesystem character substitution). Both are fixable with targeted, low-risk changes.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Root Cause Analysis\n    10→\n    11→### Failure 1: `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` → no match\n    12→\n    13→**Input structure:**\n    14→```\n    15→Line 1: Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\n    16→Line 2: & Coriander\n    17→Line 3: [body text, >80 chars, filtered]\n    18→```\n    19→\n    20→**What happens now:**\n    21→\n    22→1. `buildCandidates` generates three relevant candidates:\n    23→   - `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` (single, origin: \"single\")\n    24→   - `\"& Coriander\"` (single, origin: \"single\")\n    25→   - `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` (origin: \"2-line\")\n    26→\n    27→2. The iteration 6 `survivingJoins` block (lines 394–406) correctly removes the **prefix** single `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` because the join starts with it and the remainder (`& Coriander`) begins with `&` — a continuation character.\n    28→\n    29→3. But `\"& Coriander\"` itself remains as a standalone candidate. It passes all hard filters: 11 chars, no measurement, starts with `&` (not lowercase), two words.\n    30→\n    31→4. The dedup filter (lines 413–421) sees that `\"& coriander\"` is a substring of the join AND shorter → the join is removed.\n    32→\n    33→5. Only `\"& Coriander\"` survives (or nothing, if it falls below threshold). Either way, no match.\n    34→\n    35→**Root cause:** The continuation protection is one-directional — it removes the prefix half of a split title but not the suffix half. The suffix fragment then triggers the \"shorter wins\" dedup rule against the complete join, destroying it.\n    36→\n    37→### Failure 2: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` → no match\n    38→\n    39→**Input structure:**\n    40→```\n    41→Line 29: FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)     ← garbled OCR from previous recipe\n    42→Line 54: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK     ← correct title line 1\n    43→Line 55: / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)    ← correct title line 2\n    44→```\n    45→\n    46→**What happens now:**\n    47→\n    48→The iteration 6 changes (embedding-based `baseHeading` selection, truncation penalty, continuation extension, `survivingJoins` protection) likely produce the correct output: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`.\n    49→\n    50→**But it still fails the evaluation** because of a character mismatch:\n    51→\n    52→- The expected title (from the filename) uses `:` → `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`\n    53→- The OCR text uses `/` → `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`\n    54→- The `/` in the original cookbook text was substituted with `:` in the filename because `/` is illegal in filesystem paths.\n    55→\n    56→The `titles_match` function in `title-loop.py` performs exact normalized substring matching:\n    57→```python\n    58→extracted_norm = normalize(extracted)\n    59→expected_parts = [normalize(p) for p in expected.split(\"+\")]\n    60→return all(part in extracted_norm for part in expected_parts)\n    61→```\n    62→\n    63→`\"saffron wheat buns with quark : cottage cheese (variation d)\"` is not contained in `\"saffron wheat buns with quark / cottage cheese (variation d)\"`. The single-character difference (`:` vs `/`) causes the match to fail.\n    64→\n    65→**Root cause (primary):** The evaluation harness does not account for the filesystem character substitution. This is a data/evaluation bug, not an algorithm bug. The algorithm is likely already producing the correct output from the OCR text.\n    66→\n    67→**Root cause (secondary):** The fixed `-0.15` truncation penalty for `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` is fragile. While the embedding-quality `baseHeading` selection (iteration 6) should prefer the correct title, a hard disqualification would be more robust than a soft penalty.\n    68→\n    69→---\n    70→\n    71→## Proposed Changes\n    72→\n    73→### Change 1: Remove suffix fragments from surviving continuation joins (fixes Failure 1)\n    74→\n    75→**What:** Extend the `survivingJoins` block (lines 394–406) to also remove standalone candidates that are the **suffix** part of a surviving continuation join, not just the prefix part.\n    76→\n    77→**Where:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 394–406 — add a second filter pass within the same block.\n    78→\n    79→**Current code (lines 394–406):**\n    80→```ts\n    81→const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n    82→if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n    83→  selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n    84→    if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n    85→    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n    86→    return !survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n    87→      const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n    88→      if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n    89→      const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n    90→      return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n    91→    });\n    92→  });\n    93→}\n    94→```\n    95→\n    96→**After:**\n    97→```ts\n    98→const survivingJoins = selected.filter((s) => s.origin === \"2-line\" || s.origin === \"3-line\");\n    99→if (survivingJoins.length > 0) {\n   100→  selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n   101→    if (s.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n   102→    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   103→    // Remove PREFIX singles: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" when\n   104→    // \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" survived\n   105→    const isPrefixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   106→      const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   107→      if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n   108→      const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n   109→      return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n   110→    });\n   111→    if (isPrefixOfJoin) return false;\n   112→    // Remove SUFFIX singles: \"& Coriander\" when\n   113→    // \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" survived\n   114→    const isSuffixOfJoin = survivingJoins.some((j) => {\n   115→      const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n   116→      if (!jLower.endsWith(\" \" + sLower)) return false;\n   117→      // Only remove if the suffix starts with a continuation character\n   118→      return /^[/&+:(]/.test(sLower);\n   119→    });\n   120→    if (isSuffixOfJoin) return false;\n   121→    return true;\n   122→  });\n   123→}\n   124→```\n   125→\n   126→**Why this works for Failure 1:**\n   127→\n   128→- `\"& Coriander\"` is the suffix of the join `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"`.\n   129→- `\"& coriander\"` starts with `&` — a continuation character.\n   130→- The suffix is removed before dedup runs.\n   131→- The join survives dedup intact → correct title returned.\n   132→\n   133→**Why safe for existing tests:**\n   134→\n   135→- **Pierogi Ruskie:** The join `\"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\"` doesn't survive threshold (ingredient text scores low), so `survivingJoins` is empty or doesn't contain it. Even if it did, `\"200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\"` doesn't start with a continuation character.\n   136→- **ARAYES SHRAK:** `\"SHRAK\"` alone is 1 word, 5 chars. It may or may not pass hard filters, but even if it does, `\"shrak\"` does not start with `/&+:(`. Safe.\n   137→- **TITLE FIRST PART / SECOND PART:** `\"/ SECOND PART\"` starts with `/` and IS the suffix of the join. It would be removed. This is correct — we want the full join, not the fragment.\n   138→\n   139→**Regression risk:** Very low. The suffix removal only fires when (a) a continuation join survived the threshold, AND (b) the single candidate starts with a continuation character. This is an extremely narrow condition that matches exactly the split-title-with-continuation pattern.\n   140→\n   141→---\n   142→\n   143→### Change 2: Normalize `/` ↔ `:` in `titles_match` (fixes Failure 2 — primary)\n   144→\n   145→**What:** In the evaluation harness (`title-loop.py`), normalize `/` and `:` to a common character before comparing. This accounts for the filesystem character substitution where `:` replaces `/` in filenames.\n   146→\n   147→**Where:** `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`, `titles_match` function (line 117).\n   148→\n   149→**Current code:**\n   150→```python\n   151→def titles_match(extracted: str, expected: str) -> bool:\n   152→    if not extracted:\n   153→        return False\n   154→    extracted_norm = normalize(extracted)\n   155→    expected_parts = [normalize(p) for p in expected.split(\"+\")]\n   156→    return all(part in extracted_norm for part in expected_parts)\n   157→```\n   158→\n   159→**After:**\n   160→```python\n   161→def normalize_separators(s: str) -> str:\n   162→    \"\"\"Normalize filesystem-substituted characters (: replaces / in filenames).\"\"\"\n   163→    return s.replace(\":\", \"/\")\n   164→\n   165→def titles_match(extracted: str, expected: str) -> bool:\n   166→    if not extracted:\n   167→        return False\n   168→    extracted_norm = normalize_separators(normalize(extracted))\n   169→    expected_parts = [normalize_separators(normalize(p)) for p in expected.split(\"+\")]\n   170→    return all(part in extracted_norm for part in expected_parts)\n   171→```\n   172→\n   173→**Why this works:** The expected title `\"saffron wheat buns with quark : cottage cheese (variation d)\"` becomes `\"saffron wheat buns with quark / cottage cheese (variation d)\"` after normalization. The extracted title `\"saffron wheat buns with quark / cottage cheese (variation d)\"` also normalizes to the same. Match succeeds.\n   174→\n   175→**Why safe:** The `:` → `/` normalization only affects comparison, not the algorithm output. No other test cases use `:` in expected titles. The `+` split in `expected.split(\"+\")` happens before separator normalization, so multi-title pages like `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` are unaffected.\n   176→\n   177→**Note:** This change is in the evaluation harness (`tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`), not in `lib/text-classifier/`. It's the correct fix because the algorithm should output what the OCR says (`/`), and the evaluation should account for the filesystem encoding (`:`).\n   178→\n   179→---\n   180→\n   181→### Change 3: Hard disqualification for truncated OCR structural headings (defense-in-depth for Failure 2)\n   182→\n   183→**What:** Instead of a soft `-0.15` penalty, set the rawScore of a truncated structural heading to `-1.0` (effectively disqualifying it). This ensures that `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` can never win over `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` regardless of embedding score distributions.\n   184→\n   185→**Where:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 298–311 — the truncation penalty block.\n   186→\n   187→**Current code:**\n   188→```ts\n   189→if (hasTruncation) {\n   190→  sc.rawScore -= 0.15;\n   191→  break;\n   192→}\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→**After:**\n   196→```ts\n   197→if (hasTruncation) {\n   198→  sc.rawScore = -1.0;  // Hard disqualification — truncated OCR artifact\n   199→  break;\n   200→}\n   201→```\n   202→\n   203→**Why this works:** The embedding-quality `baseHeading` selection already prefers the correct title in most cases. But if MiniLM embeddings ever produce a score distribution where the garbled fragment still wins after -0.15, the hard disqualification ensures it's eliminated. `-1.0` is so far below any plausible score that the truncated heading can never become `baseHeading` or pass the threshold.\n   204→\n   205→**Why safe:** The truncation detection (suffix match between significant words of two structural headings) is extremely precise. It only fires when one ALL_CAPS heading has a word that is a strict suffix of a word in another ALL_CAPS heading (e.g., `FRON` suffix of `SAFFRON`). This condition is nearly impossible to produce accidentally in real recipe titles. On the Finnish Flatbreads page, `FLATBREADS` appears in both but `ow !== w` and the suffix check prevents self-matching — neither word is a suffix of the other.\n   206→\n   207→---\n   208→\n   209→## Expected Impact\n   210→\n   211→| Change | Fixes | Risk | Scope |\n   212→|---|---|---|---|\n   213→| 1. Remove suffix fragments | Failure 1 (Baked Eggs) | Very low — narrow continuation-char guard | `title-extractor.ts` lines 394–406 |\n   214→| 2. Normalize separators in `titles_match` | Failure 2 primary (evaluation mismatch) | None — comparison-only change | `title-loop.py` line 117 |\n   215→| 3. Hard disqualification for truncated headings | Failure 2 defense-in-depth | Very low — strict cross-match only | `title-extractor.ts` lines 306–308 |\n   216→\n   217→### Expected Accuracy\n   218→\n   219→- **Failure 1 (Baked Eggs):** Fixed by Change 1. The suffix `\"& Coriander\"` is removed before dedup → join `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` survives → match.\n   220→- **Failure 2 (Saffron Wheat Buns):** Fixed by Change 2. The algorithm already outputs `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` from the OCR. With separator normalization, `titles_match` recognizes it as matching the expected `\":\"` variant. Change 3 adds insurance.\n   221→- **All passing tests:** Unaffected. Changes 1 and 3 have narrow guards. Change 2 only affects the harness comparison.\n   222→- **Projected accuracy:** 8/8 = 100% on real files (up from 6/8 = 66.7%).\n   223→\n   224→### Regression Risks\n   225→\n   226→- **Pierogi Ruskie:** Change 1 does NOT remove any fragments for this case (no continuation characters in the ingredient suffix). Dedup correctly keeps the shorter form.\n   227→- **ARAYES SHRAK:** `\"SHRAK\"` doesn't start with a continuation character. The existing prefix removal handles ARAYES. No change in behavior.\n   228→- **FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS:** No truncation relationship between the two titles. No separator normalization needed. Unaffected.\n   229→- **MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD, OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH:** Single-title pages with no split titles or truncation. Unaffected.\n   230→\n   231→### Key Insight\n   232→\n   233→This iteration's changes are small and targeted because the iteration 6 improvements (embedding-quality baseHeading, thresholdScore, continuation protection) were fundamentally sound. The remaining failures are:\n   234→1. An incomplete edge in the continuation protection (prefix but not suffix removal) — a one-sided fix for a two-sided problem.\n   235→2. An evaluation harness bug where filesystem character encoding creates a false negative.\n   236→\n   237→Neither indicates a fundamental design flaw. The algorithm is working correctly for the Saffron case — it just can't get credit for it due to the evaluation mismatch.\n   238→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Mec9R64nuL6YcE5gmCxs41","session_id":"dda4a6e7-7d44-4b1e-8d84-edc63f9f063b","uuid":"3c498d6e-be55-43ee-a2bd-081649beaa22"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01N1E3gFuJXNNDVksQaxYH7q","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 6 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failures\n     4→\n     5→### 1. `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` → (unknown, result: no)\n     6→\n     7→**Input structure:**\n     8→```\n     9→Line 1: Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\n    10→Line 2: & Coriander\n    11→Line 3: Baked eggs is one of my all-time... (body, >80 chars, filtered)\n    12→```\n    13→\n    14→**Why it still fails after iteration 6's fix:**\n    15→\n    16→Iteration 6 added the `survivingJoins` continuation protection (lines 394–406) to remove the single-line prefix `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce` when the 2-line join `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` also survives. This correctly removes the prefix single.\n    17→\n    18→However, `& Coriander` (line 2, the *suffix* fragment) is itself a standalone candidate. It passes every hard filter:\n    19→- Length 11 ✓\n    20→- No measurement pattern ✓\n    21→- Starts with `&` (not lowercase) → not caught by `isLikelyGarbled` ✓\n    22→- Two words, so single-word NON_TITLE_WORDS check doesn't apply ✓\n    23→\n    24→If `& Coriander` passes the score threshold and remains in `selected`, the deduplication step (lines 413–421) removes the full join, because:\n    25→```\n    26→\"baked eggs with feta, harissa tomato sauce & coriander\".includes(\"& coriander\") → true\n    27→```\n    28→`& Coriander` is shorter → the join is eliminated. The output becomes `& Coriander` or nothing if `& Coriander` also fails other checks.\n    29→\n    30→**Root cause:** The continuation protection removes the PREFIX single, but not the SUFFIX single (`& Coriander`). The dedup \"shorter wins\" rule then kills the 2-line join via the unprotected suffix fragment.\n    31→\n    32→**Secondary possible cause:** Even if `& Coriander` falls below threshold, the 2-line join `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` (no ALL_CAPS, no structural bonus) may score significantly lower than the single-line prefix (without the diluting `& Coriander` phrase appended). If `bestThresholdScore × 0.7` exceeds the join's rawScore, the join is filtered before dedup even runs, leaving only the shorter prefix — which is still not the expected title.\n    33→\n    34→---\n    35→\n    36→### 2. `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` → (unknown, result: no)\n    37→\n    38→**Input structure:**\n    39→```\n    40→Line 1:  BUNS                              ← filtered by NON_TITLE_WORDS\n    41→Lines 2–13: garbled fragments              ← filtered by isLikelyGarbled\n    42→Line 29: FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)    ← garbled structural heading\n    43→Lines 30–53: recipe body, ingredients\n    44→Line 54: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK    ← correct title line 1\n    45→Line 55: / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)   ← correct title line 2\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→**Issue A: OCR character corruption (`:` → `/`)**\n    49→\n    50→The expected title (from filename) is:\n    51→```\n    52→SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    53→```\n    54→\n    55→But the OCR text line 55 reads:\n    56→```\n    57→/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\n    58→```\n    59→\n    60→The `:` separator was OCR'd (or rendered in the file) as `/`. Filenames cannot contain `/` on most filesystems, so the expected title was saved with `:` as a substitute. The algorithm correctly joins lines 54–55 into `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`, but the `titles_match` function performs an exact substring comparison: `\"saffron wheat buns with quark : cottage cheese (variation d)\"` is not contained in `\"saffron wheat buns with quark / cottage cheese (variation d)\"`. The match fails regardless of whether the algorithm's heuristic logic is correct.\n    61→\n    62→**Issue B: Truncation penalty may be insufficient**\n    63→\n    64→Iteration 6 added a `-0.15` rawScore penalty to structural headings whose significant words are proper suffixes of another structural heading's words (`FRON` ← `SAFFRON`). This was designed to demote `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` below the threshold.\n    65→\n    66→However, the penalty is a fixed value and may not be sufficient depending on embedding scores. If `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` has a high rawScore (e.g. 0.40), after penalty it becomes 0.25. Its thresholdScore = 0.33. If the correct join (`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`) scores lower (e.g. 0.38), its bestThresholdScore = 0.46, threshold = 0.322. In this scenario, FRON's thresholdScore 0.33 still exceeds threshold 0.322 — FRON survives.\n    67→\n    68→If FRON and the correct join both survive, the multi-title guard keeps both (two ALL_CAPS candidates). Output becomes `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1) + SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` — wrong on two counts.\n    69→\n    70→**Root cause (primary):** The OCR text has `/` but the expected title has `:` (a filesystem substitution artifact). Any algorithm output from this text will contain `/`, never matching the expected `:` substring.\n    71→\n    72→**Root cause (secondary):** The fixed `-0.15` truncation penalty may not reliably demote garbled structural headings across varying embedding score distributions.\n    73→\n    74→---\n    75→\n    76→## Common Themes\n    77→\n    78→### Theme 1: Suffix fragments survive and kill correct joins via dedup (case 1)\n    79→\n    80→The continuation protection (iteration 6) only removes the *prefix* single (`Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce`) when the join survives. It does not remove the *suffix* single (`& Coriander`). The dedup \"shorter wins\" rule then removes the join because `& coriander` is a substring of it and shorter. Fixing the prefix-side while ignoring the suffix-side is incomplete.\n    81→\n    82→### Theme 2: OCR-to-filename character substitution causes evaluation mismatch (case 2)\n    83→\n    84→The file naming convention encodes `:` in place of `/` (since `/` is illegal in filenames). When the OCR text uses `/` as a structural separator, the algorithm's output will always differ from the expected title by one character. This is a data/evaluation issue, not an algorithm issue. The algorithm may actually be extracting the correct structural heading from the OCR text but failing the match because of this encoding mismatch.\n    85→\n    86→To fix: either normalize `/` ↔ `:` in `titles_match`, or rename the input file with `÷` or another character, or treat `/` and `:` as equivalent separators when comparing.\n    87→\n    88→### Theme 3: Fixed-value penalties on embedding scores are fragile (case 2)\n    89→\n    90→The `-0.15` truncation penalty is an empirically chosen constant applied to a floating-point embedding score. Because embedding scores vary across texts, a fixed penalty can eliminate the garbled candidate in some cases but fail in others. A more robust approach would be relative penalization, disqualification (set rawScore to a large negative), or using a rule-based pre-filter to block clearly garbled structural headings before the scoring phase.\n    91→\n    92→### Theme 4: \"Shorter wins\" dedup interacts badly with split titles (cases 1 and 2, persistent)\n    93→\n    94→The dedup rule (keep shorter) is correct for ingredient run-ons but wrong for multi-line titles where both halves of the title independently pass hard filters and threshold. The continuation protection added in iteration 6 addresses one direction (prefix removal) but not both directions. The suffix fragment can still trigger the \"shorter wins\" rule against the correct join.\n    95→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Mec9R64nuL6YcE5gmCxs41","session_id":"dda4a6e7-7d44-4b1e-8d84-edc63f9f063b","uuid":"9f010546-0007-48ab-9fff-d6a40447f0cd"}
