{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017kRrePwRjsGxBPKMjXEHBK","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→2 (/½ cup plus ı tablespoon a sland mixer fried with v for s minutes, or ami tre bad\n     2→nto a loured work counter, t es and shape into ball a a\n     3→3 pan over a medium beat y i both sides. As you cook wre em on top of each other a paper towel to prevent to nd cooling down compic illing onto each Balored, at then fold the cornes in te pe. Serve with sovel.\n     4→DAT FLATBREADS\n     5→le Finnish region of Savo 1a bread, it's more like a : baked in the oven. Often lighter meal with Egg Ba: utely delicious.\n     6→time: I hour\n     7→uttermilk\n     8→shed barley groats\n     9→butter\n    10→rley groats together in mperature overnight.\n    11→ven to 200C400 F\n    12→ng sheet with baking\n    13→its to the buttermilk and mix until con-\n    14→hined. You don't need to use a stand mixer for this dough. Use your hands to spread the dough out onto the prepared baking sheet and bake for about 20 minutes, or until it has a nice colour.\n    15→For image see page 171\n    16→FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\n    17→Maitorieska (Finland)\n    18→Originally this milk-and-barley based flatbread was most common in the Finnish region of Ostroboth-nia, but today can be found pretty much across the whole country. Eat it fresh with some butter on the side and a glass of milk to drink next to it.\n    19→Preparation and cooking time: 1 hour\n    20→Makes: 8-10 pieces\n    21→500 ml/17 fl oz (2 cups plus 2 tablespoons) milk\n    22→7g/0.24 oz (½ tablespoon) salt\n    23→500g/1 Ib 2 oz (3 cups) barley flour\n    24→60 g/2¼ oz (½ cup) plain (all-purpose) flour butter, to serve\n    25→Preheat the oven to at least 250°C/480°F/Gas Mark 9, up to 350°C/660°F/highest gas mark if you can.\n    26→Mix all of the ingredients together in a bowl. The dough should be quite firm.\n    27→Divide the dough into 8-10 equal pieces. Knead the individual pieces by hand for a little while, then shape them into round flatbreads using your hands. They should be about 1 cm/½ inch thick.\n    28→Put the flatbreads on a baking sheet and prick them all over with a fork. Bake for 8-10 minutes, depending on how hot the oven is. Serve warm with butter.\n    29→FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\n    30→Perunarieska (Finland)\n    31→This soft and quite thick Finnish potato flatbread is often eaten warm with some salty butter spread on top. Perfect to make if you have leftover mashed potatoes.\n    32→Preparation and cooking time: 30 minutes\n    33→Makes: 10 flatbreads\n    34→5g/0.20 oz (1 teaspoon) salt\n    35→I egg\n    36→180 g/6½ oz (1½ cups) plain (all-purpose) flour\n    37→250g/9 oz (1 cup) leftover mashed potatoes butter, to serve\n    38→Preheat the oven to 250°C/480°F/Gas Mark 9 and line a baking sheet with baking (parchment) paper.\n    39→Add the salt, egg and flour to the mashed potatoes in a bowl and mix until it is a smooth dough.\n    40→Divide the dough into Io equal pieces and flatten them with your hands into quite thin, round breads.\n    41→Put the breads on the prepared baking sheet and bake for 8-Io minutes, or until the breads are nicely golden. Enjoy them warm from the oven with butter.\n    42→For image see page 171\n    43→175 Recipes / Flatbreads"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014SMcitGhR7RLPNfFUpgyat","session_id":"dda4a6e7-7d44-4b1e-8d84-edc63f9f063b","uuid":"58b33146-16f7-45e7-9e1a-a16de760625e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01EpB5WRiDExGrpXH9Bdxmi1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→ARAYES\n     2→SHRAK\n     3→250 g / 9 ounces\n     4→ground beef\n     5→250 g / 9 ounces\n     6→ground lamb\n     7→1 onion, finely chopped\n     8→1 green chilli, finely chopped\n     9→2 garlic cloves, finely chopped\n    10→20g / ½ cup finely chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley\n    11→1 teaspoon salt\n    12→½ teaspoon ground allspice\n    13→½ teaspoon ground coriander\n    14→½ teaspoon ground cumin\n    15→¼ teaspoon ground black\n    16→pepper\n    17→4 shrak breads (or substitute lavash, markook, or any thin bread)\n    18→1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil\n    19→1 cube of lamb fat, 20 to\n    20→50 g / ¾¼ to 1¾ oz\n    21→The best arayes (stuffed pitas) in Palestine are made in the old city of Nablus, a bustling food haven in the north of the West Bank. I always go to the best baker in the Old City, Al-Wawi, to get half-baked pita breads, and then head to Bashar Al-Mari's butcher shop, where they make the best arayes in town. The butcher expertly minces the meat in front of you, fills the pita, and bakes it in an oven, just until it is crispy.\n    22→Then he takes it out and rubs a piece of lamb fat, called liyyeh, on the hot arayes and gives them a last browning bake in the oven.\n    23→For the full experience, walk a bit further into the Old City, stop by the Al-Amad pickle shop, and get a variety of colourful pickles to enjoy with your arayes.\n    24→For this recipe, instead of using a pita, I use shrak, a thin round bread that can be rolled to make arayes. Enjoy these with yoghurt, tahinia, or a spicy dip on the side and plenty of pickles.\n    25→In a bowl, combine the beef, lamb, onion, chilli, garlic, parsley, salt, allspice, coriander, cumin, and pepper and mix by hand until evenly combined.\n    26→On a work surface, spread a shrak flat and cut it in half. Fill a half-circle of bread with 1 tablespoon of the minced meat and roll it to get a cigar-shaped araye. Repeat with the remaining shrak.\n    27→Preheat a gas or charcoal barbecue (grill) to medium-high heat or a skillet over medium-high heat. Brush the grill rack or skillet with olive oil, add the arayes and cook for 5 to 6 minutes on each side, until the outside is crispy and the filling is cooked.\n    28→Before you remove the arayes from the heat, rub a square of fat on both sides of the arayes and cook for another minute on all sides. Remove from the heat and serve.\n    29→MAKES 8 ARAYES\n    30→SPRING"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014SMcitGhR7RLPNfFUpgyat","session_id":"dda4a6e7-7d44-4b1e-8d84-edc63f9f063b","uuid":"15fbce56-ab27-47f8-986c-0c990d19123e"}
