{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01E5pWH4YKanFsy4LYTrUywR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of all four failures. Let me think through each one and propose solutions.\n\n**Failure 1: Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander**\n\nThe issue: title split across lines 1 and 2. The 2-line join exists but either doesn't survive the embedding threshold, or the suffix \"& Coriander\" passes filters and kills the join via dedup. \n\nThe feedback says the continuation-prefix-protection logic doesn't fire because the join's embedding score is below the threshold, so `survivingJoins` is empty.\n\nRoot cause: The system relies on the 2-line join surviving the threshold independently. \n\nThe problem is that embeddings might score the joined version lower than the clean first line alone, and the join protection only activates after the join already passes the threshold. Instead, I should detect continuation lines structurally—when a line starts with characters like &, /, +, :, or an open paren, that's a nearly certain signal it's a continuation, not a new title. I can use this to proactively merge those lines before generating candidates, rather than waiting for embeddings to validate the join.\n\nFor the \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" case, the multi-title guard is incorrectly treating \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" as a separate recipe title when it's actually an intra-recipe section header. The key distinction is that in this cookbook format, the recipe title always appears first structurally, before any body text or ingredient lists begin, so section headers appearing later should be filtered out.\n\nI can fix this by checking if later ALL_CAPS headings share vocabulary with the first heading—like \"WARZYWA\" appearing in both \"WARZYWAMI\" and \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"—or by using position-based logic where only the first ALL_CAPS heading at positions 0-2 counts as the recipe title. keep the first ALL_CAPS heading as the recipe title, and treat any subsequent ones as section headers only if there's ingredient-like content between them. The position matters too—if the first heading is near the top and later ones come after measurements and numbers, they're almost certainly subsections rather than separate recipes.\n\nFor the Polish example, the mixed-case title at the very start followed immediately by an ALL_CAPS transliteration is a telltale pattern: the ALL_CAPS line is a subtitle or romanization, not the main recipe title. The actual recipe name is always the first non-empty line.\n\nThe fix is to give position-0 mixed-case candidates a much stronger boost when they pass the embedding threshold—right now the position multiplier is only ×1.12, which gets drowned out by the +0.18 additive ALL_CAPS bonuses. I should either increase that position factor significantly or add a specific rule: when an ALL_CAPS heading and a mixed-case candidate sit on consecutive lines at positions 0 and 1, treat the ALL_CAPS as a subtitle and prefer the mixed-case.\n\nFor the \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" failure, there are two problems. The OCR is reading \"/\" instead of \":\" which I can't fix algorithmically without updating the eval harness. The bigger issue is that the 2-line join gets filtered out by the top-25 pre-filter because it has 9 words and the filter prioritizes ALL_CAPS and short word counts. I need to either prioritize continuation joins in the pre-filter itself, or build the joins before filtering and give them special handling. Actually, looking at the code, the continuation logic already exists—it's just a matter of making sure these joined headings survive the pre-filter.\n\nThe real insight here is that I'm treating embedding similarity as the primary signal when structural and positional cues are actually more reliable for recipes. Titles almost always appear in the first few lines, continuation lines starting with special characters should be merged rather than scored separately, and intra-recipe section headers follow predictable patterns.\n\nMy approach should be: pre-merge continuation lines before generating candidates to eliminate the fragility of relying on joins surviving thresholds, improve the multi-title guard by detecting ingredient-like content between headings to distinguish section headers from titles, and protect mixed-case titles at the start of the document from being filtered out.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6666,"cache_read_input_tokens":34818,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6666},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dda4a6e7-7d44-4b1e-8d84-edc63f9f063b","uuid":"ede29017-d385-4c90-8246-954728c2701d"}
